  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When selling an investment property in Brisbane, vendors are often advised to obtain a rental appraisal letter and include it in the marketing. The logic is straightforward: if you can demonstrate what the property will earn as a rental, you give investor buyers the data they need to calculate yield and justify their offer. In the right circumstances, a strong rental appraisal can meaningfully support your asking price. But used carelessly, it can also narrow your buyer pool or create expectations that are difficult to manage. Understanding how it works helps you use it properly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a rental appraisal letter actually is</h2>
      <p>A rental appraisal letter is a written estimate from a licensed property manager of the weekly rent they believe the property would achieve in the current market if it were tenanted today. It is based on their knowledge of comparable rentals in the area, the property's condition, and current tenant demand. It is not a valuation, it is not a guarantee, and it is not legally binding. A property manager is giving you their professional opinion of market rent, not a contractual commitment to lease the property at that figure.</p>

      <p>The distinction between a formal rental appraisal and an informal estimate matters in practice. A formal appraisal is prepared by a licensed property manager, is presented on company letterhead, and typically references comparable rental evidence. An informal estimate might be a figure mentioned verbally by an agent during an appraisal of the property for sale. Investor buyers are familiar with the difference. A formal appraisal from a credible property management company carries weight. A verbal estimate included as a line item in the marketing copy carries almost none.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How rental yield influences investor buyers</h2>
      <p>Investor buyers in Brisbane's inner east use gross rental yield as one input in their purchasing decision. Gross yield is calculated simply: annual rent divided by purchase price, expressed as a percentage. A property that rents for a given weekly figure at a given price will produce a specific gross yield figure, and investors generally have a yield threshold below which they will not purchase. If the rental appraisal supports the asking price at a yield level that is competitive with alternatives in the area, investor buyers are more likely to engage seriously.</p>

      <p>Where the rental appraisal does real work is in supporting negotiation. An investor who might otherwise push hard on price to improve their yield calculation has less room to do so when the rental evidence is clearly documented. If the appraisal is credible, recent, and from a recognised property management company, it acts as an anchor in the negotiation. The buyer knows that the rental income assumption is based on something substantive, not a number you have invented.</p>

      <p>Rental yield is not the only factor investor buyers weigh, however. They will also consider the property's capital growth prospects, the quality of the building and infrastructure, the tenant profile typical for the area, the state of current tenancy if the property is tenanted, vacancy rates in the suburb, and the management fees they will need to factor in. A strong rental appraisal supports the income argument but does not address these other dimensions of the purchase decision.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a high rental appraisal helps versus when it limits your buyer pool</h2>
      <p>The most important thing to understand about leading your marketing with rental data is that it sends a signal about who the property is for. If you prominently advertise the rental appraisal in the headline marketing, you attract investor buyers and reduce the visibility of the campaign to owner-occupiers who may actually be willing to pay more.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner-east suburbs, many investment properties are also suitable and desirable for owner-occupiers. A well-presented two-bedroom unit in Norman Park, a character home in Hawthorne, or a renovated terrace in Balmoral is likely to appeal equally to someone buying to live in as to someone buying to rent out. Owner-occupiers in these suburbs frequently outbid investors because they are not constrained by yield calculations. They are buying a lifestyle, not an income stream. If your marketing skews heavily toward rental yield data, you risk filtering out the segment of the buyer pool that might actually pay the most.</p>

      <p>The right approach depends on the property and who is realistically buying it. If the property is already tenanted, is clearly an investment-grade dwelling rather than an owner-occupier property, and is located in an area where investor demand is strong, the rental appraisal can be featured prominently. If the property has genuine owner-occupier appeal, it is often more effective to include the rental appraisal as supplementary information available on request, rather than leading with it in the headline marketing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How agents present rental income data without making unverifiable claims</h2>
      <p>There is an important compliance dimension to how rental income is presented in property marketing. Under Australian consumer law, agents and vendors are prohibited from making misleading representations about a property's rental income potential. This means you cannot advertise a rental figure that is not supportable, you cannot imply a property is currently achieving a rent it is not, and you cannot present an optimistic estimate as if it were a guaranteed outcome.</p>

      <p>Responsible practice is to present the rental appraisal as exactly what it is: an independent professional estimate of potential market rent, with the property manager's name, company, and date clearly attributed. Phrases like "rental appraisal of $X per week from [company]" are appropriate. Claims like "earns $X per week" or "rental income of $X guaranteed" are not, unless the property is tenanted and the lease confirms that figure. Your agent should be guiding you on this language. If they are not, ask directly how they intend to present the rental data and make sure it is defensible.</p>

      <p>If the property is currently tenanted, include the actual lease terms rather than relying solely on the appraisal. A current lease showing rent, expiry date, and tenant history is more compelling to most investor buyers than an appraisal alone, because it demonstrates the income is real rather than theoretical. The combination of a current lease and a rental appraisal indicating market rent is slightly higher than the current rent is often the strongest presentation available, as it shows the property is already income-producing with upside on the next lease renewal.</p>

